ce:section.ce:para:
Herein is studied a 1.4 mm thick multilayer green sample, with each 3 layers of approximately 500 µm. After gold deposition on both surfaces, the sample is preheated to T0 = 300 °C, with an effective conductivity σeff of 1.95 mS.cm-1. In this case, with an electric field E0 of 100 V/cm, the initial theoretical power is 19.5 W/cm3 (PJ = σeff · E0
                        2), superior to the empirical threshold of 10 W/cm3. The flash event was observed after 16 s (Fig. 2a
                        ). The evolution of the electric field over time reveals that the field drops from 100 V/cm to approximately 60 V/cm at the transition from voltage to current control, with a current density set at 6 A/cm2, this behavior being consistent with thermal runaway [6]. This decrease suggests a time-dependent reduction in sample resistivity following the flash, likely due to increasing temperature and microstructural changes such as neck formation between particles and porosity reduction [5]. Subsequently, a rebound in the electric field is observed at around 25 s. This phenomenon can be attributed to the loss of contact in the hotspot region between the gold electrode and the current collector due to local shrinkage of the sample, combined with gold aggregation (as illustrated in Fig. 2c). It results in the reduction of the effective contact area and an increase of the local current density leading to a sharp increase in the electric field as shown by simulation on FS process [49,50].
